This will install the packages listed in BCLFile from the
git repository configured in the same file. The first line
of the BCLFile should contain the repository address and
the next lines should contain the published package.

Example BCLFile content:
git@github.com:sample-org/sample-repo.git
sample-package1-v1.2.3-release
sample-package2-v1.2.3-release

Arch-aware resolution

For entries that do not pin a platform/arch suffix (the common case,
e.g. "sv-v2.10.0-release"), BCL picks the per-arch release branch that
matches the host:

  1. <entry>-<host_arch>   preferred — e.g. -arm64 on Apple Silicon
  2. <entry>               legacy unsuffixed branch (runs under Rosetta
                           on Apple Silicon)
  3. <entry>-amd64         Apple Silicon only; prompts before installing
                           (skipped on Linux arm64 — Rosetta is macOS-
                           specific, so an amd64 binary would not run)

On Linux arm64, steps 1 and 2 still apply. If you need to pin an
amd64 branch on a non-macOS arm64 host, use --no-arch-resolve.

If you accept the amd64 fallback on an arm64 host, the choice is cached
at cli/.bcl-arch-choice and reused on later runs so you are not reprompted.
When a native arm64 build later lands for the same entry, BCL detects it,
removes the cached fallback, and reinstalls with the native build.

The cache key includes the exact entry string, so bumping the version in
BCLFile re-evaluates automatically. If you switch to an amd64 build by
other means (e.g. --no-arch-resolve) and want BCL to upgrade you to a
later-published arm64 build, run with --reset-arch-choice once.

Flags:
  --no-arch-resolve     Resolve each entry literally as written; do not
                        try arch-suffixed variants. Escape hatch for
                        pinning a specific branch.
  --reset-arch-choice   Drop cli/.bcl-arch-choice and force reinstall of
                        every entry in this invocation. Use to
                        re-evaluate without bumping versions.

Environment variables:
  BCL_AUTO_FALLBACK_AMD64=1   Auto-accept the amd64 fallback on arm64
                              hosts (for CI and non-interactive contexts).
  BCL_FORCE_ARCH=amd64|arm64  Override host arch detection. Useful for
                              testing and for containers whose effective
                              arch differs from the host kernel.

Add cli/.bcl-arch-choice to your project's .gitignore — it is per-developer
state, not source code.
